data.content:
## What Breaks

In .NET 11, the Cosmos DB provider **removes the `AllowSynchronousIO` opt-in entirely**. Every synchronous LINQ operation (`ToList()`, `First()`, `Count()`, `SaveChanges()`) will throw `InvalidOperationException` at runtime — there's no configuration to re-enable it.

The Cosmos DB provider never had true sync I/O; it was always sync-over-async internally, which risks threadpool starvation and deadlocks. .NET 10 let you opt in to that behavior; .NET 11 eliminates the escape hatch.

## The Fix

Convert all sync calls to their async counterparts:

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

**Key changes:**
- `ToList()` → `ToListAsync()`
- `First()` → `FirstAsync()`
- `Count()` → `CountAsync()`
- `SaveChanges()` → `SaveChangesAsync()`
- All return types wrapped in `Task<T>`, methods marked `async`

This is **not optional** — it's a compile-time design change. Callers up the chain must also go async (`async`/`await` propagates up through controllers, etc.).
